## The claim being probed

A committed atlas record is not a receipt; it is a **program**. From
the record alone — zero new f-evaluations — the typed engine can
compute futures that were never run: what a classical instrument WILL
do under counterfactual configurations (every midpoint it will visit,
where it will stop, what it will claim), and what the lattice WILL
look like at precisions beyond the measured grid. Each reconstruction
is graded against an ACTUAL re-run. Where the record cannot warrant a
prediction, the organ refuses — typed, never a guess.

## Scope

- **Leg 1 — bisection futures from the certified cell.** The I1a sign
  comparison `(f_mid > 0) == (f_lo > 0)` is, on a single-crossing
  bracket, *same-side-of-the-certified-cell* — so the committed
  terminal cell determines I1a's entire trajectory at ANY xtol by
  pure arithmetic. Reconstruct (stop value, claim, stop rule, n_iters,
  and the full visited-point sequence) for a pinned fixture × xtol
  grid; grade against the committed I1a code object actually re-run
  under the counterfactual rule entry (the rule dict is data; the
  instrument code is untouched), with a recording shim capturing its
  true evaluation points.
- **Leg 2 — flow counterfactuals beyond the grid.** From committed
  facet-D records + law arithmetic alone (no rounder calls in the
  organ): dyadic-death and cluster-split booleans at pinned q beyond
  the measured 1..60 grid; graded against fresh referee rn executions.
- **Refusal arms.** No certified crossing (FXE1, FXB4: certificate
